, are often flouted - but also at the wider legal issues arising from child soldiering: to what extent can child soldiers be held criminally liable for their conduct? How should they be treated when captured? How are states obliged to demobilise and reintegrate them into their societies? It also identifies a move away towards enforcement, through the prosecution of those who recruit child soldiers, and proposals for Security Council sanctions against governments and groups who breach their international obligations by using children in armed conflicts.This study will be essential reading for those concerned with public international law, human rights, and the United Nations and peacekeeping.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aSecurity Council sanctions.  aThe United Nations.  aarmed forces.  achild soldiers.  acriminal liability.  ainternational law.  apeacekeeping.  areintegration.  awar.1 aHappold, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152617047740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526170477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526170477/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles